2 1/2 years after the Emancipation Proclamation was signed there were STILL slavery practiced in Texas Juneteenth (short for “June Nineteenth”) marks the day when Union federal troops arrived in Galveston, Texas in 1865 to take control of the state and ensure that all enslaved people be freed. Last year @potus made it a federal holiday to remember and commemorate. Y’all see where I get it from right??? This is my dad messing with my nephew. Clifton Campbell (my daddy) was a hero to so many. He worked in child care his entire career. It was important that he reach kids from impoverished areas. He worked in group homes. He was a chess master and used the game to reach and teach kids from all over but had a special place for young ppl on the spectrum and for those who were surrounded with nothing but disadvantages. He was a self taught magician and would entertain young ppl by doing tricks or stirring up a fiery game of Simon Says. He gave it up and dropped everything for several years to help my son Xen after we got the autism diagnosis and  together dad, we made miracles happen. That was my dad… I miss you and yes it’s beyond heartbreaking but I feel like God and you are guiding me, my sisters, and my brothers thru this. Dad, you would be so PROUD of us. No matter what, me and my siblings are sticking together.  No one can break us. No weapon formed against us. We are Campbell strong TOGETHER. I remember being 3 years old holding onto your knee and looking up at you thinking “ My daddy is the biggest strongest man in the world.” It was hard to watch you endure the pain in these last years but you are beyond earthy body experiences now and you’re not in pain anymore. I can’t help but smile because Jesus has you now. Don’t worry about me dad…Every time a tear falls it’s quickly replaced with funny or  beloved memories. I can’t help but laugh thinking of you dude! You are my angel and I know you’re in heaven helping navigate and protecting me and my sons. Feeling like we GOT our own SUPER POWER! . #blessed #jesusishealing #campbellstrong #loveyouwithallmysoul

A rare moment captured… it was a rarity to catch me without a smile on my face. My parents had to scrape together their last in order for me to take this school picture. I felt bad for them. I was young, but I understood… I understood our financial disparities. I understood I had to help my family. I understood I had to be a leader and a big sister to my little brothers. So much pressure but even then, I felt it was important to keep things light and keep a  smile on my face… I still feel that way.

We lost another queen. RIP Ellen Holly who was hailed with being THE first black woman ever to star in a soap opera …. In 1968 “One Life To Live” and then again in the 80’s in a “Guiding Light” She also spoke up and out for the way her fellow African-American thespians on soap operas  were being mistreated. I was lucky enough to work with her when I was about 9 years old in a play in the historic “The Henry Street Playhouse” and again when I was 18 years old in the movie “School Daze”  You were a  majestic and your work will NOT be forgotten 🕊️🕊️🕊️🙏🏼🙏🏼🙏🏼
